= demonsarise
## Demons Arise
To this settled way of thinking come demons…

Drawing arabesques with wheelies exemplifies following one's nose. We more-or-less design from what we see. See a compass; imagine a wheelie. Post-and-lintel, to be sure, but post-and-lintel works just fine — thank you — in all that doors require for letting people get around.

But along come arches — a disruptive technology, where disjoint rock may span greater distances than contiguous lintels — which, perforce, break if spans are too long. For wheelies, what disrupts is the [inverse discrete Fourier transform](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_Fourier_transform#Inverse_transform). With it we may ditch step-and-repeat; the transform plots the entire arabesque in just one throw.

The shiv that cuts is this: Wheelies are cognates of _frequency domain_ ordinates. These inhabit a discrete, one dimensional parameter space: the frequency domain. A single complex ordinate situated on the abscissa charts a time domain counterpart, an oscillating or spinning thing. That spin's offset from a reference direction, its _phase_, is analogous to the ordinate's argument and the length of the spinning thing — a vector — aligns with the ordinate's magnitude. The discrete Fourier tranforms, forward and inverse, interconnect frequency domain ordinates to time domain oscillations; see [Figure 5](#figfive).   
= figfive
===
![spectralspace](images/spectralspace.svg)
*5. Plotting _kth_ wheelie sum in a one dimensional, discrete, circular and finite frequency domain.*
===

|      1.  |The frequency domain is discrete, finite and circular:
|      1a.  |Its origin corresponds to a rotation rate of zero. Discrete frequencies, _ω_, mark off the abscissa. These are commensurate with wheelies' rotational rates.
|      1b.  |The abscissa wraps around. Clockwise and counterclockwise rotational coordinates extend from the origin's left and right, respectively, meeting at a _folding_ or [Nyquist sampling rate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyquist_rate) (_n_). This sets the space's extent: _2·n_.
|      1c.  |For _n_ odd, it is moot whether _ωn_ imposes clockwise or counterclockwise rotation on its allied temporal spinner, as that vector alternates between its azimuth and 180° opposite. As this produces the same results either way, one can't declare whether clockwise or counterclockwise rotation is at hand.
|      1d.  |As a consequence of folding, addition and subtraction are [modular](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic). Subtrahends more positive than their minuends do not make negatives but induce as many implied additions of extents as necessary to put the results into the interval _0,…,2·n–1_. Similarly, addends exceeding the extent invokes implied subtractions to bring the results into the same interval.
|      2.  |A frequency domain ordinate may specify a _plane position vector rotation around an origin_. Ordinates, being complex, set both the magnitude (vector length) and phase (angular offset) of the vector from a reference direction. One need not squint very hard to see in this spinning vector a wheelie. Medieval cosmologists in the Ptolemaic school might also see _epicycles_.
|      3.  |A minimum Nyquist sampling rate may be chosen to distinguish, within one period, _at least_ two distinct orientations of the most rapidly spinning wheelie.

Transforming the frequency domain by way of the inverse discrete Fourier transform produces an aggregate oscillatory signal of complex values in the time domain; see [Figure 8](#figeight). These trace the ultimate wheelie tip on the complex plane — shown by [Argand diagrams](#fignine). The path of the wheelie tip is cognate to the image in the frequency domain. That image may be plotted through the following scheme:

= mapwheelies
### Mapping Wheelies to the Frequency Domain
|      1.  |It's essential not to plot _single_ wheelies in the frequency domain but _sums_. That dictate stems from chaining: A wheelie reflects both its own and the spins of its antecedents. Similarly, a wheelie reflects both its own and antecedents' orientations.
|      2.  |Starting from the root wheelie, initialize aggregate sums for orientation, _Σθ_, and rotational rate, _Σω_, with the orientation of the root, _θ₀ → Σθ_, and the root's rotational rate, _±ω₀ → Σω_.
|      2a.  |If _Σω_ < 0, add twice the Nyquist rate: _Σω + 2·n → Σω_ in accordance with modular arithmetic.
|      3.  |With the current wheelie, decompose its radius, _r_, into complex components: _r_ → _r·cos(Σθ) + i·r·sin(Σθ)_.
|      4.  |Add this decomposed complex radius to the value at frequency domain coordinate _Σω_.
|      5.  |If there are no further wheelies in the chain, branch to 7. Otherwise:
|      6.  |Proceed to the next wheelie in the chain from the root. Add its orientation, _θ_, and rotational rate, _ω_, to aggregate sums:  _θ + Σθ → Σθ_, and _ω + Σω → Σω_.
|      6a.  |If _Σω_ < 0, then add the Nyquist rate: _Σω + 2·n → Σω_ in accordance to modular arithmetic. Branch to 3.
|      7.  |We've finished plotting. The inverse discrete Fourier transform generates the arabesque; we exit.
