## To There And Back Again
Suppose we already have an arabesque, or, more broadly, an arbitrary shape topologically equivalent to a circle, but which has been suitably worked over by an Old School ash, 18 inch Louisville Slugger® so as to appear, say, like a 1911 Goudy Bookletter ampersand, over which some tutorial writers appear to be obsessed. Are there wheelies that could generate it?
= figten
===
| ![goudyampersand](images/ampersand_circ.svg)
|*10. Circle ~~slightly~~ ~~somewhat~~ substantially dented into the shape of a 1911 Goudy Bookletter ampersand*
===
Yes, because the bidirectional discrete Fourier transforms, forward and inverse, generally operate on all periodic forms, be they in a time-varying traversal-of-paths form, or the corresponding frequency domain image. From a frequency domain image, we might then assay a reverse form of [Mapping Wheelies to the Frequency Domain](#mapwheelies), extracting wheelies from their sums.

In light of that, let us regard an "arabesque" to be any path which is topologically equivalent to a circle. We'll hijack the measure of angular displacement along a circular circumference to also represent the relative amount of travel along such a "bent-up-circle" path. With that, we then take measure of the complex coordinates of a point traveling uniformly along such a path. Their real and imaginary components fluctuate in time, and, as the point completes 360° circuits, the variations are periodic. Taking the forward discrete Fourier transform of this time-varying fluctuation generates the correspondent frequency domain image. This is commesurate with the arabesque, the transform coupling the path and its frequency domain image.

So far, so good: we have arrived at the arabesque's frequency domain image. From there we might consider running [Mapping Wheelies to the Frequency Domain](#mapwheelies) backwards, somehow, separating wheelie sums out into the wheelies themselves.

That, for the moment, may engender a certain angst. Are there similar — _unique?_ — couplings of wheelie chains to frequency domain images? And, by extension, to the particular arabesques?

[Mapping Wheelies to the Frequency Domain](#mapwheelies) suggests that we can put our angsts to rest, difficult as that may be for Brooklynites. Reviewing that scheme reminds us that particular ordinates plotted in the frequency domain arise from wheelie _sums_, and there are any number of ways to add up terms to arrive at particular sums: get 7 from 6 + 1. Or 4 + 3. Similarly, any number of wheelie chains give rise to the same frequency domain image. For example, consider the wheelie chain _Xn_:

|- wheelie | radius (_r_)| orientation (_θ_)| spin (_±ω_)|_Σθ_|_Σω_|_r·cos(Σθ)_|_i·r·sin(Σθ)_
| *   1* | *   2* | *  3* | *  4* | *  5* | *  6* | *     7* | *     8*
|X₀|0.5|30°|+1|30°|+1|0.43301|0.25000
|X₁|0.5|15°|+2|45°|+3|0.35355|0.35355
|X₂|0.125|30°|2n-7|75°|2n-4|0.03235|0.12074
|X₃|0.25|15°|+3|90°|2n-1|0.00000|0.2500

Or _Yn_:

|- wheelie | radius (_r_)| orientation (_θ_)| spin (_±ω_)|_Σθ_|_Σω_|_r·cos(Σθ)_|_i·r·sin(Σθ)_
| *   1* | *   2* | *  3* | *  4* | *  5* | *  6* | *     7* | *     8*
|Y₀|0.5000|30|+1|30|+1|0.43301|0.25000
|Y₁|0.2500|60|2n-2|90|2n-1|0.00000|0.25000
|Y₂|0.5000|314|+4|44|+3|0.35967|0.34733
|Y₃|0.125|32|2n-7|76|2n-4|0.030240|0.12129

These are different wheelie chains, yet running each chain through the [Mapping Wheelies to the Frequency Domain](#mapwheelies) process result in the same frequency domain image. They may arrive at the ordinates in different sequences, but in the end generate the same image. Compare columns (5) and (6), the aggregates resulting from the process among the various progenitors of the frequency domain image; they are all the same and, following an inverse discrete Fourier transform, all would give rise to the same loop-de-loop arabesque of [Figure 9](#fignine).

This eases our burden. Our search for wheelie chains that could generate 1911 Goudy Bookletter ampersands becomes one of finding _any_ wheelie chain that sums to the desired frequency domain image.

More formally, any pair-wise differencing chain of a permutation _a_ of the _n_ non-zero ordinates in a frequency domain image will yield the _n_ following wheelies:
= figeleven
===

$$
\begin{matrix}
W_{0} & = & a_0 \\
W_{1} & = & a_1 - a_0 \\
W_{2} & = & a_2 - a_1 \\
& \vdots & \\
W_{k} & = & a_k - a_{k-1} \\
& \vdots & \\
W_{n} & = & a_n - a_{n-1} \\
\end{matrix}
$$
*11. Finding a wheelie chain through some permutation of frequency domain ordinates*
===

with the root wheelie stemming from the initial permuted ordinate. If we're fastidious about the entire series being one of differences, then we may think of this first ordinate as differencing against zero. By this pairwise differencing, then, any ordinate _ak_ in the frequency domain image arises from the wheelie sum: _ak_ = Wk + Wk-1 + … + W₁ + W₀.

Our scheme of finding wheelie chains runs along these lines.

|      1.  |Digitize the path: obtain discrete samples of the path at (presumably) equal time steps.
|      2.  |Find the frequency domain image of these samples through the discrete forward Fourier transform.
|      3.  |Compute the wheelies through any pair-wise differencing chain of a permutation _a_ of the non-zero ordinates in the frequency domain image. 

While, in principle, we could use any permutation of non-zero ordinates, there is a practical aspect of differencing first the low-rotational ordinates: in the vast majority of cases, the oscillations with the largest swings — those that capture the essence of the path — tend to low frequencies. These are the ordinates with the largest magnitudes, and, in the translation to the time domain, constitute the most significant path-shaping oscillations.


